    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1978-06-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1978-06-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="114"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d114">
                <head>114. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_VC_1"
                        >Vance</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d114fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Subject File, Box 20, Evening Reports
                        (State) 6/78. Secret. <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName>
                        initialed “C” in the upper right corner.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1978-06-20">June 20, 1978</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Zaire</hi>. The western ambassadors have begun meetings with
                        <persName corresp="#p_MSS_1">Mobutu</persName> to urge that he undertake
                    serious reform in Zaire. Giscard called <persName corresp="#p_MSS_1"
                        >Mobutu</persName> to stress the importance of the five-power demarche, and
                        <persName corresp="#p_MSS_1">Mobutu</persName> received the French
                    Ambassador yesterday. We understand that <persName corresp="#p_MSS_1"
                        >Mobutu</persName> told the French that he agreed with the points made in
                    the five-power memorandum.<note n="2" xml:id="d114fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d112fn7">footnote 7, Document 112</ref>.</note> In response to
                    the French Ambassador’s suggestion that relations with Angola be improved,
                        <persName corresp="#p_MSS_1">Mobutu</persName> said that he was willing to
                    try to reach an understanding with <persName corresp="#p_NAA_1">Neto</persName>
                    but was skeptical about what could be achieved. Kaunda, he said, has offered to
                    mediate.</p>
                <p>Our Ambassador made his demarche today and delivered your letter.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d114fn3">See <ref target="#d112">Document 112</ref>. <persName
                            corresp="#p_CWL_1">Cutler</persName> reported on his meeting with
                            <persName corresp="#p_MSS_1">Mobutu</persName> in telegram 6429 from
                        Kinshasa, June 20. (National Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy File,
                        D780256–1242)</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MSS_1">Mobutu</persName> read the letter carefully and
                    bristled momentarily at references to corruption, arrests, and executions. His
                    comments were defensive, but he asked that we be assured that he is aware of the
                    need to expedite reform.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here are items unrelated to Central Africa.]</p>
            </div>
